<br>
The people of the world are happier if the UN is at least seen to be functioning as an institution of world order. (It is only because Bush has treated it with such contempt that there is such a huge anti-war movement going on.)<br>
<br>
At least that is my view.<br>
<br>
However I posted the 'pax americana' article as information.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Bush certainly did not campaign on such a change. It is not something that he or others have dared to discuss honestly with the American people. To the contrary, in his foreign policy debate with Al Gore, Bush pointedly advocated a more humble foreign policy, a position calculated to appeal to voters leery of military intervention.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As I said, I neither agree nor disagree with the point of view it describes. (My own hope would be for a US willing to share these immense responsibilities.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Are peace and security best achieved by seeking strong alliances and international consensus, led by the United States? Or is it necessary to take a more unilateral approach, accepting and enhancing the global dominance that, according to some, history has thrust upon us? <br>
