<br>
However the fighting is not over yet, and are you in any way aware of the awful humanitarian crisis (a hackneyed phrase I know) that is now going on there?  The looting, the anarchy, the hospitals almost at breaking point, the utterly miserable state of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>most</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Iraqis now that their social structure has been destroyed?  Or perhaps you simply do not care about these things.<br>
<br>
Your tone seems to be a bit like gloating triumphing to me btw. I can understand the pride you must feel at how bravely the Coalition troops acquitted themselves against such a rich, powerful, well armed and dangerous opponent, but consider how much better the world will respect you if you refrain from such self-indulgence.  To be considered truly civilised, the victor should be magnanimous and noble, should (at least try) to be self-effacing and put the velvet glove over the iron fist (imho), don't you agree? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=talche>Talche</A> at: 4/10/03 9:13:26 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=timberwind@nuclearspace>timberwind</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/10/03 7:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=405.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: We are winning!</span><hr size=1> Talche,<br>
<br>
  Touch a nerve?  I'll give you credit, at least you showed up.  <br>
<br>
&quot;However the fighting is not over yet, and are you in any way aware of the awful humanitarian crisis (a hackneyed phrase I know) that is now going on there? The looting, the anarchy, the hospitals almost at breaking point, the utterly miserable state of most Iraqis now that their social structure has been destroyed? Or perhaps you simply do not care about these things.&quot;<br>
<br>
What's the focus here?  Yeah, there's a humanitarian crisis in Iraq caused by a war.  What did you expect?  Would you have us leave Saddam in power because that's better than a humanitarian crisis caused by his removal from power?  Why don't you ask the Iraqi's which they prefer?  <br>
<br>
&quot;Your tone seems to be a bit like gloating triumphing to me btw. I can understand the pride you must feel at how bravely the Coalition troops acquitted themselves against such a rich, powerful, well armed and dangerous opponent, but consider how much better the world will respect you if you refrain from such self-indulgence. To be considered truly civilised, the victor should be magnanimous and noble, should (at least try) to be self-effacing and put the velvet glove over the iron fist (imho), don't you agree? &quot;<br>
<br>
Blah, blah, blah.  Please save the Euro-snob attitude for someone who gives a sXXt.  Coalition forces blew away Iraq.  If that sounds like gloating to you, too bad.  Still doesn't change the fact that coalition forces pulled off a great military and political feat.  And coalition forces aren't rubbing the victory in Iraq's face.  <br>
<br>
Who said the following, bub;<br>
<br>
&quot;No quick victory, no mass uprising against Saddam, no bunkers full of weapons of mass destruction, and precious little honour.&quot;<br>
<br>
Let's see, that makes you ... what ... 1 for 4.  Saddam is gone, inside of 3 weeks.  The Iraqi's didn't need to have a mass uprising against Saddam because Saddam was gone [once again] inside 3 weeks.  Are you really going to stand by the WMD statement?  After all, Saddam only gassed 10,000 Kurds in the late 80's, but hey, they're only Kurds and evidently don't count according to your rhetoric.  And getting rid of Saddam was a very honorable endeavor.  Thank God Tony Blair saw it that way. <br>
 <br>
&quot;I can understand the pride you must feel at how bravely the Coalition troops acquitted themselves against such a rich, powerful, well armed and dangerous opponent, but consider how much better the world will respect you if you refrain from such self-indulgence.&quot;  <br>
<br>
I 'm pretty confident the world respects what the U.S. can do.  If they don't and they're a country that wants to harbor terrorists or loony tune dictators with a history of using WMD, then they better start packing.<br>
<br>
In closing, I'll tell you something.  I like the British.  They have been a loyal ally to America for the last couple hundred years (discount the Revolutionary War and War of 1812 please).  And America has been likewise to Britain.  The war in Iraq exposed the real reason most anti-war types in Britain and Europe (and the yahoo element in America) were against America.  And Talche, you said it best.  I'll quote you again;<br>
<br>
&quot;But Bush rubs me up the wrong way, and he has that effect on a lot of Europeans&quot;<br>
<br>
Let me ask you something.  Did you protest when Clinton went around the U.N. and bombed Serbia?  Where were all the millions of Europeans protesting that war?    <br>
<br>
I hope you get used to being &quot;rubbed&quot; the wrong way.  This Bush is a lot like Reagan.  And Reagan was adored by most of Western Europe, wasn't he? &lt;sarcasm&gt;  I'll take the Reagan and Bush II legacy over any legacy produced by an American President the Europeans liked (Clinton, Carter).  <br>
